Track Every LLM Token in Node.js: A Lightweight npm Package for Input/Output Usage Monitoring
If you’re building with OpenAI, Anthropic, or any LLM API, you’ve probably asked yourself:
“How many tokens did that request actually use?”
Token usage drives cost, performance, and scaling decisions. Yet in many Node.js apps, usage data lives buried inside API responses — logged once, then forgotten.
I built all-llm-token-tracker to solve this: a small, focused npm package that tracks input and output tokens for every LLM call, with pluggable storage and built-in support for popular providers.

The problem
Most LLM integrations look like this:
const response = await openai.chat.completions.create({ … });
console.log(response.usage); // sometimes logged, rarely stored
That’s fine for debugging — but not for production. You typically need:

• Per-call input and output token counts

• Storage you can query later (not just console logs)

• Summaries by model, provider, or user

• A setup that works in dev and production
Existing tools often bundle pricing, dashboards, or heavy infrastructure. Sometimes you just want clean token tracking with flexible storage.

The solution: all-llm-token-tracker
npm: all-llm-token-tracker
GitHub: rkanumetta/all-llm-token-tracker
License: MIT
What it does

• Records token usage per LLM call (inputTokens, outputTokens, totalTokens)

• Wraps any async LLM function with tracker.track()

• Built-in extractors for OpenAI and Anthropic response shapes

• Pluggable storage:

• Memory — great for tests

• File — local JSON persistence

• MongoDB — production database storage

• Query calls and get summaries (totals, averages, group by provider/model)

• Optional browser dashboard to visualize usage
What it doesn’t do (by design)

• No billing/pricing engine

• No vendor lock-in

• No required external services
It focuses on one job: track tokens reliably.

Installation
npm install all-llm-token-tracker
For MongoDB storage:
npm install all-llm-token-tracker mongodb
Requirements: Node.js 18+

Quick start: manual recording
The simplest way to track usage — pass token counts directly:
import { createTracker } from ‘all-llm-token-tracker’;
const tracker = createTracker({ storage: ‘memory’ });
const record = await tracker.record({
provider: ‘openai’,
model: ‘gpt-4o-mini’,
inputTokens: 120,
outputTokens: 45,
metadata: { userId: ‘user-123’ },
});
console.log(record.totalTokens); // 165
Every record gets a unique ID, timestamp, and optional metadata — useful for auditing and per-user analytics.

Auto-track LLM calls (recommended)
Wrap your existing LLM function. The tracker records usage automatically:
import {createTracker,extractOpenAiUsage,} from ‘all-llm-token-tracker’;
import OpenAI from ‘openai’;
const tracker = createTracker({
storage: ‘file’,
file: { filePath: ‘./.llm-usage/usage.json’ },
});
const openai = new OpenAI();
const { result, record } = await tracker.track(
() =>
openai.chat.completions.create({
model: ‘gpt-4o-mini’,
messages: [{ role: ‘user’, content: ‘Hello!’ }],
}),
{
provider: ‘openai’,
model: ‘gpt-4o-mini’,
extractUsage: extractOpenAiUsage,
metadata: { feature: ‘chat’ },
}
);
console.log(result.choices[0].message.content);
console.log(record.inputTokens, record.outputTokens);
What happens under the hood:

• Timer starts

• Your LLM function runs

• Usage is extracted from the response

• A record is saved to storage

• You get both result and record back
No changes to your core LLM logic — just a wrapper.

Anthropic support
Same pattern, different extractor:
import { extractAnthropicUsage } from ‘all-llm-token-tracker’;
await tracker.track(
() => anthropic.messages.create({ /* … */ }),
{
provider: ‘anthropic’,
model: ‘claude-3–5-sonnet-20241022’,
extractUsage: extractAnthropicUsage,
}
);

Storage options
1. Memory (testing & scripts)
const tracker = createTracker({ storage: ‘memory’ });
Fast, in-process. Perfect for unit tests.
2. File (local development)
const tracker = createTracker({
storage: ‘file’,
file: { filePath: ‘./.llm-usage/usage.json’ },
});
Persists to a JSON file you can inspect, back up, or feed into a dashboard.
3. MongoDB (production)
const tracker = createTracker({
storage: ‘mongodb’,
mongodb: {
uri: process.env.MONGODB_URI!,
database: ‘my_app’,
collection: ‘llm_token_usage’,
},
});
// when shutting down
await tracker.close();
MongoDB is an optional peer dependency — only install it if you need it.

Query and summarize usage
Once data is stored, query it:
const calls = await tracker.getCalls({
provider: ‘openai’,
from: ‘2026–07–01’,
limit: 100,
});
const summary = await tracker.getSummary();
// {
// totalCalls: 42,
// totalInputTokens: 12500,
// totalOutputTokens: 3200,
// totalTokens: 15700,
// averageInputTokens: 297.6,
// …
// }
const byModel = await tracker.getSummaryByModel();
const byProvider = await tracker.getSummaryByProvider();
Example summary output:
MetricValue
Total calls 3
Input tokens 463
Output tokens 179
Total tokens 642

Record structure
Each call is stored as:
{
“id”: “uuid”,
“provider”: “openai”,
“model”: “gpt-4o-mini”,
“inputTokens”: 120,
“outputTokens”: 45,
“totalTokens”: 165,
“timestamp”: “2026–07–10T06:00:00.000Z”,
“durationMs”: 842,
“metadata”: { “userId”: “user-123” }
}
Clean, predictable, and easy to pipe into analytics tools.

Custom providers
Not using OpenAI or Anthropic? Create your own extractor:
import { createUsageExtractor } from ‘all-llm-token-tracker’;
const extractMyProviderUsage = createUsageExtractor((response) => ({
inputTokens: response.tokens.in,
outputTokens: response.tokens.out,
}));
Or implement a fully custom StorageAdapter (Postgres, Redis, etc.):
import { createTracker, type StorageAdapter, type LlmCallRecord } from ‘all-llm-token-tracker’;
class PostgresStorage implements StorageAdapter {
async save(record: LlmCallRecord): Promise<void> { /* … */ }
async find(query) { /* … */ }
async count(query) { /* … */ }
}
const tracker = createTracker({ storage: new PostgresStorage() });

Visual dashboard (bonus)
The package includes a simple browser dashboard for input/output visualization:
npm run example
npm run dashboard
Open http://localhost:4173
You’ll see:

• Total calls, input tokens, output tokens

• Bar chart per call

• Breakdown by model

• Filterable table with metadata
You can also open dashboard/index.html and load your usage.json file directly.

Real-world use cases
Use caseHow this helps
Cost monitoring
Track input/output tokens per feature or user
Debugging
See which prompts consume the most tokens
A/B testing
Compare token usage across models
Rate limiting
Build custom limits from stored usage data
Compliance
Audit trail with timestamps and metadata
SaaS billing
Feed token data into your own pricing logic

Why I built it this way
1. Small surface area
One responsibility: track tokens. No magic.
2. Storage flexibility
Start with file storage in dev, move to MongoDB in production.
3. Provider-agnostic
Built-in OpenAI + Anthropic extractors, easy to extend.
4. TypeScript-first
Full type definitions included.
5. Zero required dependencies
MongoDB is optional. The core package is lightweight.

Final thoughts
LLM token tracking doesn’t need to be complicated. With a thin wrapper around your API calls and a consistent record format, you get observability that scales from a weekend project to production.
Track input. Track output. Store it. Query it. Done.
